quote: Why didn't you say you could?
Affirmative! Talk to it!

Open hailing frequencies! Crystal Form, I identify myself as "Data," advising you to stop your attack. The humans here are powerful, capable of injuring or even destroying you. They can be changed only in other ways.
Now I call that communicating.
But he mentioned "changing us," Captain. What does that mean?

It has many meanings, as any human language dictionary could inform you. Suggest moving fast to confirm what I told it, sir. Permission to use the large transporter in Cargo Room Three? There I can beam out some living pattern, perhaps a large tree...
Which you'll beam over next to the entity...
You are correct, Riker. Our ship's phasers will then blast and disintegrate it... proving we're dangerous.
Make it so!
Sir?
Do it!
Sir, I know this may finish me as an acting ensign, but...
Shut up, Wesley. Lieutenant Yar, pick a good security team, let me know what he does.
"Shut up, Wesley?"
Stay out of this, Madam...
Since I am finished here, Captain, may I point out... ?
Shut up, Wesley!
... that what I've said would have been listened to if it came from an adult officer. Request permission to return to my quarters, sir.
Granted, if you take your mother with you.
You're putting me off the bridge?
I'm asking that you keep an eye on your son during this, Doctor.
Please, Mom. Let's go.
Emergency close!
Now show me your warrior fierceness.
I'll look, but I should never have let you talk me into this...
It's Data, Mom. He's been hurt!
It's Data! For once will you trust me about something?
You must know how much Starfleet means to me. But I'm finished unless you can help me. I heard you know how to turn them on. Please?
No, this is very serious...
I know, Mom. So tell me again to "shut up, Wesley," and I will.
You're being very unfair, Wesley...
Data, the Crystal Thing is outside close to the ship... and Lore is loose somewhere inside.
How badly are you hurt... Data?
I will function sufficiently to stop Lore, Doctor...
Whatever happens, it is important that you two stay away from him. Do not try to help me.
Good, you understand perfectly so far. Next, I'll signal I'm about to transport something out...
... at which time the deflector shields will turn off for a moment, and if you move in at that time...
How sad, dear brother. You have made me wish I were an only child.
Then why this marvelous gift, my brother? The troublesome little man-child. Are you prepared for the kind of death you've earned, little man?
If you take one step toward my son...
Ah, motherhood! Back off or I'll turn your little man into a torch!
I promise him exquisite pain unless you obey me too, dear brother.
Move away, Data, please!
Do you see now the advantages of being completely human? It includes kindness. I give you your life, Doctor. Go, quickly and I may not injure your son at all.
I will stay with Wesley, Doctor.
Go! Or he'll be shrieking on the count of five. One... two...
I'll bring help, Wesley.
Thank you for my human quality, Doctor Soong. Now a small payment for your son's misdeeds.
Mom!
Stay back, Wesley! Help me some other way!
Wesley... now!
Lore's gone, sir, permanently!
Now that your son's safe, Doctor, report immediately to Sickbay.
Captain... The crystal thing has begun to move away.
(continuing; beat; eyeing him) Data, get rid of that damned twitch! And put on a correct uniform.
Yes, Captain.
And Ensign Crusher... ... are you able to return to duty now?
Yes, sir!
Then do so! Let the bridge know all is well down here.
It's gone, sir. Without Lore, it had no way to reach us.
And we're overdue for our computer refit. Number One, have you ever considered whether Data is more human, or less human than we want?
I only wish we were as well balanced, sir.
Agreed!
You're worried.
With reason.
About Worf, or about Commander Riker?
Both. I think perhaps it is best to be ignorant of certain elements of the Klingon psyche.
Above, look out!
It's over.
The exercise is over.
At ease, Lieutenant!
Exit Holodeck.
You do this every day?
No -- usually my calisthenics are more... (he searches for the right word, then settles for) ... intense, but those sessions are too personal to be shared.
I'll bet they are.
Computer. Program complete -- save.
Coming Commander?
Right behind you.

Captain's log, Stardate 42193.6. We are on a long reach toward the Morgana Quadrant, a section of the galaxy which has yet to be visited by a manned Federation vessel. We are using the time to further detail the charts of this region.
There it is again. An area of "blackness."
It appears, then disappears, then reappears. There is no predictable pattern -- no sequence.
On screen.
There it is.
I can't see anything. Magnify section two-eight-five.
There -- it looks like a "hole" in space.
We're acquainted with the "wormhole" phenomenon. This appears quite different.
What do sensors indicate?
Nothing.
Nothing?
I'm sure you must mean it's empty of matter, Mister Data. There is always some energy form at work...
Sir, our sensors are showing that to be an absence of everything. It is a void without matter or energy of any kind.
Yet, this "hole" has a form, Data. It has height, width...
Perhaps. Perhaps not.
That is hardly a scientific observation, Commander.
Sir, the most elementary and valuable statement in science... the beginning of wisdom... is: "I do not know." I do not know what that is.
Captain, if this were any ordinary kind of hole in space... ... wouldn't we be able to see what's behind it?
Counselor?
I can feel nothing from it, sir, if that's what you're asking.
Data -- is there any record of any occurrence even vaguely similar to this?
"Similar" in even the slightest way.
Accessing. Negative. There is no record of any Federation vessel encountering anything remotely like this.
I believe we have time for a closer look, Number One.
Concur. Ensign, slow to one-half impulse. Adjust course to intercept this... this whatever it is.
Scanning and recording as we go.
Changing course to intercept in... in twelve minutes, sir.
Let's send a probe into it.
Worf, prepare a scanner probe. Let's see what's in there.
Close enough, Ensign. Hold this position.
Aye, sir. Holding this position.
You may launch the probe when ready, Mister Worf.
All the probe's systems are functioning perfectly.
It's gone.
What happened, Data?
Unknown.
Recommend we go to a Yellow Alert, sir.
Why?
Sorry, sir, it's...
Explain.
This starship operates best, Mister Worf, when we all know what is on each other's minds.
My thoughts... were of an old Klingon legend of... of a gigantic black space creature which was said to devour entire vessels...
Devours vessels?
Sorry, Commander. I agree that these are thoughts hardly worthy of a trained and practical security officer.
Launch another probe, Mister Worf. This time a Class One with full sensor array.
Launching, sir.
Happened even more quickly.
Recommend we fire a photon torpedo, Captain.
Negative.
Captain, based on where the probes disappeared... I have been able to plot the outer boundaries. I could move in closer.
Take us in, Mister Crusher. Thrusters only.
Data?
Still no readings of any kind, sir.
Number One?
I'll agree with Worf at this point, sir. Let's be careful.
What's happened?
Data?
Whatever it was... or whatever it is... we seem to be inside of it.
Didn't that happen a bit suddenly, sir?
All stations, report!
Captain's log, supplemental. While exploring a strange area in space without any form of matter or energy...
... a total void, we have unexpectedly seemed to enter it. Apparently we moved past its mysterious outer boundary.
All stations have reported, Captain. There seems to be no immediate threat to our ship or crew.
In which case, let's hold position for awhile, Number One. This is worth studying.
Incredible. It's like looking off into... infinity, sir. Remember the course in ancient history at Starfleet Academy? Back to the time when men still believed the Earth was flat?
And that the sun revolved around the Earth...
And if a ship sailed too far out into the ocean it would fall off the edge of the world...
"Beyond this place there be dragons."
Data -- how long to complete your scans? Let's not stay any longer than we have to.
Captain, we have no communications outside of the void.
Confirm! We are now receiving no signals of any kind.
Hello, Doctor. You've been briefed on what's happened?
I've heard, Captain. But I don't understand it.
I wish I could say I did. Increase magnification by ten.
By one hundred!
I'm not a bridge officer, but isn't this... "impossible," sir?
Increase by one thousand, Mister Data. By ten thousand.
(continuing; indicates Data) It does know how to do these things, doesn't it?
Commander Data knows precisely what he is doing.

Forgive me, Mister Data. I'm not accustomed to working with... with non-living devices that... (stops, bites off her words) Forgive me again. Your service record says that you are alive and I must accept that.
Engineering!
Engineering, aye.
Lieutenant, are your systems functioning?
Yes, sir. Wherever we are, sir, it seems to have no effect on any Engineering function.
Thank you, Lieutenant.
Data?
Difficult to make a judgment based on the absence of information.
Speculate.
The obvious hypothesis is equivocal. This void has a total lack of dimension. Therefore by any accepted standard it does not exist, yet being within it denies that conclusion.
Then maybe we've moved into another dimension?
Could a lack of dimension be another dimension in itself?
That's an interesting question.
For a later discussion. It's time we got on with our mission, Number One. Starfleet can send out a science vessel to investigate further. Let's move back out of this.
Aye, sir. Reverse our direction and set a course for the Cornelian star system. Warp two.
Reversing direction, sir. Course laid in.
Engage.
Our engines have engaged, haven't they, Ensign?
Aye, sir.
Everything all right up there, Captain?
Are the engines operating normally, Engineer?
Everything looks fine here, sir.
We're increasing to warp four, Engineer.
We now show warp four, Captain.
We should be seeing stars by now, Data. How far have we come?
Inertial guidance shows seven parsecs traveled, Captain.
Ensign Crusher?
Confirm, sir. Exactly what my readings say.
Engineering, transfer to bridge.
What's happening, sir? I thought we should have broken clear.
We should have. We're on a reverse course.
Full stop, helm.
Full stop, sir.
According to this we're well past the point we entered the void.
Except that we are still in it, sir.
Captain... if we dropped a stationary beacon and navigated straight away from it, we would have a fixed point of reference to confirm speed and distance.
Make it so, Data. Lock onto the beacon, and keep it dead astern.
The beacon is in place, Captain.
Dead ahead. Impulse power.
The beacon is falling astern.
Engineering, report.
All systems normal, sir.
Prepare to increase to warp two.
Aye, sir.
Captain, we are receiving a signal from dead ahead.
Maybe you've found the door out of this.
We are closing on the new signal, Captain.
Identify.
Captain, it is the stationary beacon we just released.
We must have come full circle, sir.
We couldn't have, sir. I've shown us steadily moving away from that beacon.
All stop; hold position again.
(indicating the viewscreen) Look.
Captain, sensors indicate a disturbance in sector one-zero- eight. Possibly a vessel.
Perhaps some answers at last. On screen.
The ship is equipped with a cloaking device.
Romulan!
It's closing.
Shields up. Go to Red Alert!
I'll be at my duty station in Sickbay.
It's uncloaking.
Arm your photon torpedoes, Mister Worf.
Hold for my orders.
There!
Direct hits, sir. Our shields are weakening.
Warn them we'll return fire.
Transmitting.
They've armed another full spread, sir.
Fire torpedoes.
That was too easy.
Yes.
Captain, sensors can locate no debris from the Romulan ship.
Captain, there is another vessel approaching -- sector zero-nine- one, mark, two-six.
Specifics.
On screen.
Magnify.
It's a Federation ship. N-C-C... one-three-oh-five dash E. It is the USS Yamato, our sister ship.
The Yamato is nowhere near this quadrant.
Open a hailing frequency, Data....
This is the USS Enterprise to... USS Yamato. Respond, please...
This is the USS Enterprise calling USS Yamato. Please respond on this frequency.
No response, Captain.
Make a full scan.
Life support system -- engineering and propulsion all seem functional. (turns; reacts at a reading) But there are no life signs over there, sir.
Can we be getting a false reading, Data?
Since we know nothing at all about these circumstances, that is... at least, conceivable, sir.
You look doubtful, sir.
I'm not anything right now, Number One. I'm just a man looking for answers.
Like the rat said -- "Keep the cheese, I just want out of the trap."
Captain, request permission to board the Yamato with an away team. There might be something onboard -- in the logs -- which will at least tell us what happened.
Granted. Minimum complement.
Worf. You're with me.

Captain's log, supplemental. We remain like a fly in amber trapped in the void. We have encountered a vessel which appears to be the USS Yamato. All its systems are shown as functioning, yet it seems devoid of life. Commander Riker is leading an away team -- hopefully the answer lies over there.
scene: 64   EXT. SPACE - THE ENTERPRISE AND THE USS YAMATO

quote: Do you have a lock on that other ship?
Aye, sir. No problems at all.
Can you put us on the bridge?
Anywhere you say, Commander.
I am acquainted with the Yamato, Commander. Recommend the Aft Station of their bridge. When in doubt, surprise them.
Them? Who's them?
Whoever may be there.
Sensors show no life signs.
Still, the tactic is sound.
Agreed. Aft Station.
Aye, sir.
Phasers on stun, Lieutenant Worf.
(continuing; to Transporter Chief) Energize.
This isn't the bridge.
No -- don't fire.
I heard you screaming. I was coming to help.
Help me? But I heard you cry out.
(touches his communicator) Transporter Chief, where do you show us over here?
We show... as approximately...
Captain, do you read me?...
... having difficulties...
Number One, come in!
Transporter Room, this is the captain. We are out of contact with the away team. Beam them back, immediately.
I have lost the lock on them.
Nothing on my communicator, sir.
Computer, on.
Let's find a turbolift to the bridge.
Transporter Room -- have you been able to establish a lock?
Initiate full check -- all systems.
Engineering section, report. What is our situation?

This isn't a Federation ship. The walls are not tritanium... close, but it's a material beyond our technology. (he then leads the way to the turbolift) Let's get to the bridge. Somewhere there must be an answer to all of this.
Wait -- if you go through there... where will you be?
scene: B84	INT. USS YAMATO - MAIN BRIDGE

quote: On the bridge.
scene: B84	INT. USS YAMATO - MAIN BRIDGE

quote: But we are on the bridge.
scene: B84	INT. USS YAMATO - MAIN BRIDGE

quote: Should I continue?
scene: B84	INT. USS YAMATO - MAIN BRIDGE

quote: Yes -- move out. Let's see what happens.
scene: B84	INT. USS YAMATO - MAIN BRIDGE

quote: Is it the same bridge?
scene: B84	INT. USS YAMATO - MAIN BRIDGE

quote: ... Or did we just step from one bridge to another bridge?
scene: B84	INT. USS YAMATO - MAIN BRIDGE

quote: Captain! I have a star fix.
On screen.
It's an opening, sir.
Confirm, navigation is possible.
Should I set a course?
Transporter Room. Do you have a fix on the away team?
Negative.
Commander.
scene: D84	INT. USS YAMATO BRIDGE - WORF

quote: At ease, Lieutenant! At EASE!
scene: D84	INT. USS YAMATO BRIDGE - WORF

quote: The star fix is fading.
Haskell, lock on to the Yamato with the tractor beam. We leave together.
I can't make the lock.
Captain. The star fix is fading.
Let it go, Data.
But, sir, we can get out.
Let it go.
Bridge, I've re-established contact with the away team.
The Yamato's beginning to fade out, Captain.
Come in, come in Enterprise.
Hold position, away team. I've got you. We are bringing you home!
Transporter Room, hurry!
Captain, it's almost gone.
What the hell's going on?
Are you all right, Number One?
Yes, but I've had it. Let's put all this technology and computers to work -- figure out what's going on -- and get the hell out of here.
A ship that was almost the Yamato, existing in a "hole in space," no crew aboard -- what's the purpose?
Add to it an attack by a nonexistent Romulan vessel, it does suggest an interesting question: "Was our away team even over there?"
If we weren't over there, where the hell were we?
Captain, I have re-established the star fix.
Great.
Set course -- velocity -- warp two.
Course and speed set.
Engage.
I have lost contact.
What?
The star fix is gone.
Sir, it is not in the same sector. But another opening has appeared.
On screen.
Set a course for those stars. Warp six.
Yes, sir -- warp six.
I have lost the signal.
Damn it.
All stop.
Captain...
I know Data, I can see it.
This game is now wearing very thin.
Hold this position. Counselor, you have said you sensed no intelligence behind all of this. You haven't changed in that belief?
I'm not so certain of that now, Captain. I do sense something unusual about all this...
Perhaps a different level of consciousness?
An intelligence so vast it eluded me? Yes, perhaps.
Rats in a maze.
Exactly!
Explain.
Everything we've been through reminds me of a laboratory experiment. As though something were testing our responses to stimuli.
Are you suggesting we're in some kind of laboratory?
Yes.
The opening seems closer, Captain.
We're finished with being led about this way.
Agreed, Captain. Hold present position.
Good. Don't satisfy its curiosity.
Why are you so alarmed when I've gone to such trouble to look just like you?
Return to your position, Lieutenant.
Sir... ?
Captain, sensors show nothing out there. Absolutely nothing.
It's a damned ugly nothing.
I am Captain Jean-Luc Picard of the USS Enterprise. ... representing a Federation of planets in this part of the galaxy. Can you identify whoever or whatever you are?
NAGILUM!
Speaks right out for something your sensors say isn't there, Data.
We've still no idea of what you represent.
"Data."
Nagilum?
You are of different construction than the others. Interesting.
Picard... Riker... Geordi... Wesley...
What are you? Your construction also differs.
My "construction"... ?
Perhaps referring to your gender.
Yes, I see... There are minor differences. I am what we call a "female."
I understand. The masculine and the feminine.
It is the way in which we propagate our species.
Please demonstrate how this is accomplished.
Not likely.
Whatever you are, your actions are not welcome.
Let me put up the shields, sir.
Our sensors do not show anything there, Worf.
Your life-form surprises me more and more. Is it also true that you have only a limited existence? Answer!
What information do you want? I don't understand the question.
You exist -- and then you cease to exist. Your minds call it "death."
How interesting.
Sickbay?
It won't help. The body is already cold.
We cannot allow you to do that! We'll fight you...
(interrupting; VOICE BOOMING) To understand death, I must amass information on every aspect of it, every kind of dying. The experiments shouldn't take more than a third of your crew, maybe half.
Captain's log, Stardate 42194.7. It is obvious that whatever we have met sees no value in our kind of life-form. How do we fight something that both is...
... and is not there?
I can sense this much. We are unimportant to it.
In a battle for survival, Captain, thirty to fifty percent casualties...
... Would be appalling...
... But within acceptable limits.
This is not a battle, Lieutenant.
A "laboratory experiment" would be the closest comparison.
Is there any reason for not believing this Nagilum?
No.
All evidence indicates he is willing and able to do what he proposes.
Agreed. Under the circumstances -- there is only one decision. I will not stand by and watch while half of my crew is slaughtered.
Sir... I do not believe there is anything you can do to prevent it.
No. But I can control it.
How?
By destroying the Enterprise.
Isn't that like curing the disease by killing the patient?
At least it's better than standing by helplessly and dying.
Why do I feel this may not have been the best time to join this ship? I'll be in Sickbay if I'm needed.
I will be at my station, Captain.
Recognize Picard... Jean-Luc...
Recognize Riker... William T.
Initiate auto-destruct sequence.
Does Riker... William T. concur?
I do. Initiate auto-destruct sequence.
What is the desired time interval?
Stand by. Interesting question. How long to prepare to die?
Which is the least painful to our crew? Move to it quickly? Or take time to prepare for it thoroughly?
Hell, twenty minutes sounds like a nice round figure. Can we do that?
The latest program allows it.
Initiate auto-destruct in twenty minutes.
Twenty minutes to auto-destruct, mark.
Nineteen minutes, fifty seconds...
Come.
Our destroying ourselves won't change its mind. I could feel that.
You didn't mention you were that certain.
I was wrong not to tell you, Captain. And your decision may also be wrong.
Yes? Come in, please.
I have a question, sir. What is death?
You've picked probably the most difficult of all questions, Data.

Some explain it by inventing gods wearing their own form... and argue that the purpose of the entire universe is to maintain themselves in their present form in an Earth-like garden which will give them pleasure through all eternity. And at the other extreme, assuming that is an "extreme," are those who prefer the idea of our blinking into nothingness with all our experiences, hopes and dreams only an illusion.
Which do you believe?

Considering the marvelous complexity of our universe, its clockwork perfection, its balances of this against that... matter, energy, gravitation, time, dimension, pattern, I believe our existence must mean more than a meaningless illusion. I prefer to believe that my and your existence goes beyond Euclidian and other "practical" measuring systems... and that, in ways we cannot yet fathom, our existence is part of a reality beyond what we understand now as reality.
We should not let ourselves die, Jean-Luc!
I agree with her, Captain.
If only half of us live, I prefer to take my chances on being one that does.
Yes. It's wrong of you to force us into this...
It is wrong...
Yes, this is very wrong. None of you should be reacting like this.
Computer, locate Commander Data.
Commander Data is on the bridge.
It's not going to work, Nagilum.
Captain, we are clear. We are out of the void.
It's gone, Captain -- we can abort the auto-destruct.
Hold, Number One.
But...
Hold.
Fifty seconds to auto-destruct.
Thirty seconds to auto-destruct.
Captain, we are clear of the void. You may stop the auto-destruct.
Data, on any heading -- warp six -- now!
Captain.
I don't believe it, Number One. It could still be part of the illusion. Data, report.
All navigational systems confirm -- we are at warp six -- on course...
Ten seconds to auto-destruct. Nine seconds. Eight seconds. Seven seconds... Six seconds...
... to the Morgana Quadrant.
Five seconds. Four seconds...
Troi?
It's gone, Captain. I no longer sense its presence.
Abort auto-destruct sequence.
Three seconds. Two seconds... Riker, William T. Do you concur?
Yes! Absolutely! I do indeed concur! Wholeheartedly!
A simple "yes" would have been sufficient, Number One.
I didn't want there to be any chance of a misunderstanding.
He sure held that bluff to the last second.
What bluff?
Well, Nagilum... I hope you got what you needed.
You have provided me with much more than I needed...
Why did you release us? You could have seen how we faced death.
It wasn't necessary. I have learned all I needed to know. Would you like me to share some of my conclusions?
I'm not interested.

Of course you are. You are too inquisitive not to want to know. You seem to find no tranquility in anything. You struggle against the inevitable. You thrive on conflict. You are selfish, yet you value loyalty. You are rash, quick to judge, slow to change. It's amazing you've survived. Be that as it may -- as species, we have no common ground. You are too aggressive. Too hostile. Too militant.
During this period, you too have been evaluated. It would seem we have at least one thing in common.
Oh?
Curiosity.
The point is well taken, Captain. Perhaps that is a trait we share.
Then perhaps we'll meet again. But next time, it will be out here among the stars.
Put us back on course, at warp three.
Warp three, sir...
And Ensign -- let's give any holes a wide berth.

Captain's log, Stardate 42486.3. We have arrived on station at coordinates -- three-six-two- nine-mark-five-eight-four, three days early for our rendezvous with USS Victory. There is nothing to do now, but hold this position and wait.
Yes, Commander?
Is there a problem? Chief Engineer La Forge called for me. "Urgent!"
Oh, of course. He's over there with the Victory.
I just had a strange conversation with your assistant. Although it is three days until we rendezvous with Starship Victory, she...
She believes it has already arrived. But not the starship, my friend. The original!
This is my gift to Starship Victory's Captain Zimbata.
Ah, most unusual.
I served as an ensign under him. I wish he'd been in command of this Victory. Wind and sail, that's the proper way to move a ship.
But your Starfleet specialty, my friend, is antimatter power, dilithium regulators...
Which is exactly why this fascinates me. Data, it's human nature to love what we don't have. Simpler days! While stringing this rigging, I was dreaming of sail handling and...
This is not a computer simulation?
Data, the entire point of something like this is to hand make it.
Just as you have used Old England in a hobby of your own.
Geordi... your message said "urgent."
And it is, my friend. While we wait to rendezvous with Victory, we have time for me to be Watson.
More properly, your Watson.
My Watson?
You've seen my dream adventure... now let me share in one of yours.
Ah, yes. Yes, my dear colleague, that does seem only fair.
I'll be gone awhile, Clancy. See that no one touches this!
Aye, sir. And where can I reach you?
He can be reached at 221B Baker Street.
Sir?
Computer -- select at random a mystery by Sir Arthur Conan Doyle, where I will play Sherlock Holmes and Lieutenant La Forge will be Doctor Watson.
Program complete -- you may enter.
Excellent.
scene: 9    INT. HOLODECK - THE SITTING ROOM AT 221B BAKER

scene: 9    INT. HOLODECK - THE SITTING ROOM AT 221B BAKER

scene: 9    INT. HOLODECK - THE SITTING ROOM AT 221B BAKER

quote: This?
scene: 9    INT. HOLODECK - THE SITTING ROOM AT 221B BAKER

scene: 9    INT. HOLODECK - THE SITTING ROOM AT 221B BAKER

scene: 9    INT. HOLODECK - THE SITTING ROOM AT 221B BAKER

quote: The snuff box of Wilhelm Gottsreich Sigismond von Ormstein.
scene: 9    INT. HOLODECK - THE SITTING ROOM AT 221B BAKER

quote: All right -- you solve the cases and get the gifts, what do I do?
scene: 9    INT. HOLODECK - THE SITTING ROOM AT 221B BAKER

quote: Primarily as Doctor Watson, you keep a written record of everything I do for later publication.
scene: 9    INT. HOLODECK - THE SITTING ROOM AT 221B BAKER

quote: And the famous Holmes violin. He purchased this in a pawn shop in Tottenham Court Road for fifty-five shillings, which he considered a very good investment.
scene: 9    INT. HOLODECK - THE SITTING ROOM AT 221B BAKER

quote: In the hands of some, the violin is a wondrous thing, equally capable of stirring the soul to the heights of bliss as to the depths of despair...
scene: 9    INT. HOLODECK - THE SITTING ROOM AT 221B BAKER

quote: Incredible, Data! How can you play it like that?
scene: 9    INT. HOLODECK - THE SITTING ROOM AT 221B BAKER

quote: Merely throwing myself into the part, Watson.
scene: 9    INT. HOLODECK - THE SITTING ROOM AT 221B BAKER

quote: In the masterful grasp of my friend, Mr. Sherlock Holmes, the violin ceases to be a musical instrument at all and becomes...
scene: 9    INT. HOLODECK - THE SITTING ROOM AT 221B BAKER

quote: Watson! We are about to have guests.
scene: 9    INT. HOLODECK - THE SITTING ROOM AT 221B BAKER

quote: Answer it, Watson -- let's not keep the good inspector waiting.

scene: 9    INT. HOLODECK - THE SITTING ROOM AT 221B BAKER

scene: 9    INT. HOLODECK - THE SITTING ROOM AT 221B BAKER

quote: What was the point to going onto the Holodeck?
To solve a Sherlock Holmes mystery.

Exactly, but, you've got them all memorized. The first time someone opens their mouth, you've got it solved. So, there's really no mystery. If there's no mystery... there's no game... no game... no fun.

I'm not angry with you, Data, really... It's just that... we go to all the trouble to arrange time to come down to the Holodeck, to get the proper wardrobe, to get into character, and, boom, it barely gets started and you jump to the end. See, I was looking forward to the chase.
Then I should have extended the sequence of events.
I'm not getting through. The fun of the program is the attempt to solve a mystery.
That is exactly what we were doing.
You are wasting your breath, Lieutenant.
Saying that to Data is asking a computer not to compute.
Am I so different from you, Doctor? Can you cease thinking on command?
In medicine I face many puzzles to which I do not know the answer.
She's right, Data. You always know the answer.
To feel the thrill of a victory... there must be the possibility of failure. Where's the victory winning a battle you can't possibly lose?
Are you suggesting that there is some value in losing?

) Yes. That's the great teacher. We humans often learn more from a mistake or a failure than we do from an easy success. But not you -- all your learning is by rote. To you it's all memorization and recitation.
I don't know about that. Deductive reasoning is Data's strength.

Yes, Holmes as well, but Holmes also understood the human soul. Those dark flecks which drive us... which turn the innocent to the evil. That understanding is beyond Data. It comes from "life" experience -- which he doesn't have -- combined with human intuition for which he cannot be programmed.
I disagree -- totally.
His victory at playing Sherlock Holmes is just a blind mimicry, a collection of bits and bytes of information without any true understanding.
You're being unfair.
I don't think so, Lieutenant. Your artificial friend wouldn't have a prayer of solving a Holmes mystery which he hasn't read.
I have read them all.
Maybe the computer could create one in the style of Holmes... where you wouldn't know the outcome.
Like I said, he wouldn't have a prayer.
I accept your challenge, Doctor.
Good for you, Data.
We will return to the Holodeck and I will dare it to defeat me, and you Madam are invited to be a witness.
I wouldn't miss it.
I've never been so hot in all my life -- are these clothes really necessary?
Believe me, you'd feel out of place without them... Just wait 'til you see our Holodeck, you'll swear you've actually been sent back to nineteenth century England.
Presuming I don't pass out first.

The Victorians believed that any form of nudity was immoral... In fact, they not only covered up all people from head to toe, but they even went so far as to put skirts and cuffs and sleeves on the arms and legs of furniture. I have instructed the computer to give us a Sherlock Holmes-type problem, but not one specifically written by Sir Arthur Conan Doyle.
So this will be something new, something created by the computer?
Exactly. Will that be sufficient, Doctor?
We'll see.
Program complete -- you may enter.
Pies, pies, Some are meat, Some are sweet, They're all the best... Pies... pies...
You're a handsome one mister... shame to stay out here in the cold...
Very impressive.
Your first visit to the Holodeck, Doctor?
How 'bout you deary... Want to get out of the fog?
First time on one with this level of sophistication. Now how does this work? The real London was over a hundred square miles in size.
This is no larger than the Holodeck, of course. So the computer adjusts by placing images of more distant perspectives on the Holodeck walls...

But with the image so perfect you'd have to touch the wall to know it was there. And the computer fools you in other ways. I say, Holmes, where shall we head -- the theatre? Rule's? Or perhaps a concert?
Stop him. He stole my goods...
No. It is a ruse. This way.
But, Data, what's over here?
What are you up to, Data? Tell us.
The running man was a hoax. The real crime is here. And the intended victim -- is...
... that man. Mr. Jabez Wilson. Employee of the Red-Headed League, dupe of a gang of criminals.

I saw the plaque - "The Home of the Red-Headed League"... and this rope dangling from the vent, which enabled me to deduce that Mr. Jabez Wilson is coming here to meet a most distasteful and untimely demise. From this...
Fraud. You didn't deduce anything. You simply recognized elements from two different Holmes stories. Fraud.
Reasoning from the general to the specific -- is that not the very definition of deduction? Is that not the way Sherlock Holmes worked?

Fraud. Variations on a theme. Now... now do you see my point? All he knows is what is stored in his memory banks. Inspiration -- original thought -- the true strength of Holmes is not possible for our friend. I give you credit for your vast knowledge, but your circuits would just short out when confronted by a truly original mystery. It's elementary, dear Data.
We will just see whose circuits short out, Doctor.
Computer! Arch!
Are you really sure you want to put yourself through this, Lieutenant? Better wilted laurels than none at all.
Computer, override previous programming. All right, now a program that definitely challenges Data.
It has to deal with events he has no previous knowledge of.
Computer, in the Holmesian style, create a mystery to confound Data with an opponent who has the ability to defeat him.
Define parameters of the program.
What does that mean?
The computer wants to know how far to take the game.
You mean it's giving you a chance to limit your risk.
No, the parameters will be whatever is necessary to accomplish the directive. Create an adversary capable of defeating Data.
What was that?

quote: Lieutenant?
scene: C22	INT. MAIN BRIDGE - ANGLE INCLUDING WORF AND

quote: An odd surge of power, sir. It's gone now.
scene: C22	INT. MAIN BRIDGE - ANGLE INCLUDING WORF AND

quote: Interesting. The same London but... slightly different.
Hello, matey. For a few bob, I can put some color in your cheeks...
No thank you.
"No thank you" is it? Rather hand it over to them...
Is something wrong, Professor?
I... I feel like a new man. (looks around; indicates) That dark man used the word "arch" and then... I wonder? "Arch."
What have we here?
Computer, standing by.
What are you?
If you refer to the arch you ordered, it provides computer control. Do you wish to input any commands?
Not at this time.
Aii! It's dark magic, Moriarty.
The best kind, I'm sure. But I need information.
Data -- I mean... Holmes old boy, what are we looking for?
For whatever finds us, dear Watson.
She has been abducted.
I think she's hiding. She's going to lead you on a wild goose chase and then recount the story to everyone between here and Alpha Centauri.
Watson -- a trail...
Leading to the alley... (then in Holmesian fashion, he continues) The doctor has been carried off by two men. One is tall -- a seaman. The other is shorter, left handed, and employed in a laboratory.
Left handed? And works in a lab? How do you know that?

One set of footfalls are widely spaced with the uneven gait particular to seamen. The other set is evenly spaced -- closer together. Further, you can see on the ground the swirling scrapes made by his left shoe as he twists back presumably to see if he is being followed. Left footed, means left handed. The dark coloration of the scrapes are the leavings of natural rubber -- a type of non-conductive soles used by researchers experimenting with electricity. Finally, there can be no argument -- the game is afoot! Come, Watson!
Hear that? What do those footfalls tell you, Watson?
That we're on the right track?
More particularly, that our opposition does indeed consist of two men... that one of them is carrying the bound and gagged Doctor Pulaski. We must hurry --
You know all this because you read it in a Holmes story, right?

Not at all... Since we do not hear the doctor's footfalls, we must presume she is being carried, and since we do not hear her calling for help, we know she is gagged. Further... both sets of footfalls are heavy and masculine -- one man seems to shuffle and stumble in an irregular pattern... Since the ground is level, I must conclude that Doctor Pulaski is struggling against her captor, sporadically knocking him off stride. It is deduction, pure and simple... well, perhaps not that simple.
Here we go, Watson -- I daresay we have caught up rather nicely with our quarry --
There should be a doorway.
Holmes, thank God you're here.
Make way, please, make way, make way for Mr. Sherlock Holmes...
It's murder, Holmes, murder most foul.
Well, Holmes, let's hear it.
There is nothing here of relevance. I do not see how this connects with the disappearance of the doctor.
Doctor? Doctor Watson is standing right here, Holmes.
Doctor Kate Pulaski. But do not concern yourself, Inspector. You have enough on your mind.
She was with you?
Inspector, perhaps I can be of assistance... As I take note of this dead man, I deduce that he was strangled.
The finger marks on his throat indicate the cause of death, and, since there are signs of a struggle, it's obvious that his killer was a stranger, who caught him from behind.
Is that correct, Holmes?

No. Look at his shoes. He's more a convict -- released just today from Dartmoor prison... He spent the day in a tavern where he consumed large quantities of gin -- with his killer, who followed him to this spot -- and waited over there until the victim slipped into a drunken stupor, then out of fear, motivated only by self-protection strangled him.
There is your killer, Inspector.
And when you check, I believe you will find this poor soul is the victim's common law wife, who has been dreading his release because he was a vile and abusive man.
But, Holmes she doesn't have the strength of strangling him.
Not with her hands -- no. But with this.
When used as a garrote, these beads will leave marks quite similar to fingerprints, except, my dear Watson... the marks on the victim are too evenly spaced to be caused by human hands.
Astounding, Holmes... absolutely astounding.
Inspector -- for reasons strictly personal -- I must leave. Come, Watson, this murder is not connected with our case.
If this murder isn't connected to the disappearance of Doctor Pulaski, then the computer is running an independent program.
Yes.
Why?
I do not know... and that troubles me.
Then you don't know what's coming next?
No.
(still enjoying the game) That's what I wanted to hear.
Do you have some coppers for a hungry man?
I'll give you some value for your copper, mate...
Allow us to pass.
Give it up.
Ain't no men left in London.
Release my coat or I will be forced to give you a severe thrashing.
It's getting a little rough. Where to, now?
We will find Doctor Pulaski inside.
How do you know that?
It is the only obvious choice.
Why, all of a sudden would the obvious choice be the correct choice? Isn't this a game of misdirection?
Not any more. He wants us to find him.
Who does?
The master criminal. The man Holmes could only defeat at the cost of his own life at Reichenbach falls - our adversary, my dear Watson is none other than Professor Moriarty himself.
Great -- now this is really getting good.
There's nothing in here but these barrels.
... and a trail. (indicating the tracks in the dust) Which is so well marked, that obviously we are meant to follow it.
Another dead end.
No Watson, not a dead end at all. Here -- can you see these scratches?
The doctor was right, now we have a game worth playing.

quote: Tell me -- stop and tell me, man!
Data! What's going on?
We must leave.
What's on the paper?
Why does it frighten you, Holmes?
Computer! Exit!
Will you please tell me what is going on?
Computer. Execute a complete shutdown of the Holodeck.
Access denied.
Explain.
Override protocol has been initiated.
The program is still running. It didn't shut down.
We must see the captain.
What is it? What's on the paper? Why can't you shut down the Holodeck? Data -- wait.
This.
This isn't possible. How could a character from 1890 London be able to draw a picture of our starship? Who has control of the computer?
He does -- Moriarty.
How is that possible? I don't understand.
Neither do I.
What about the doctor? Is she all right?
No. She is in grave danger.
Computer. Tell me. Why wasn't the Holodeck program terminated?
The override protocol has been initiated.
On whose authority?
Lieutenant Geordi La Forge.
Me?
Tell me again -- exactly what happened.
Doctor Pulaski and I had a discussion about whether Data could solve an original Holmes-type mystery.
And you asked the computer to provide one.
Yes... with a worthy opponent.
Worthy of Holmes?
Oh, my God. I asked for a Sherlock Holmes-type mystery with an opponent capable of defeating Data. That must be it.
Terrible!
Captain... I'm sorry...

I understand, Lieutenant. Well, at least now we have part of an explanation. The computer is not trying to confound "Holmes," which would be relatively easy, it has been ordered to create an adversary to defeat Data.
... I got carried away...
That's past. Data, this character Moriarty... you said he called for the arch...
Yes.
So he is able to access the computer.
And perhaps also our library files. That level of information would be necessary in order to create a true adversary for me.
Theorize, Data. What are his limits?
He is still a fictional character, originally programmed with nineteenth century knowledge.
But with access now to the twenty-fourth century.
What does he need to begin making use of that?
Only time.
Sir, I can lead a security team to sweep the Holodeck, find the Doctor, and bring her out.
Captain, I believe that would place the doctor at risk. It is probable that the mortality failsafe has been overridden.
Computer, locate Doctor Pulaski.
Doctor Pulaski is on Holodeck Two.
And her vital signs?
Strong and stable.
Counselor Troi, have you a sense of our opponent?

It is difficult for me to separate a single individual from all the disorder I feel down there. Captain, what is unusual about this is that I should not be able to sense a holographic projection at all -- yet I do.
Captain, recommend we try to destroy the hologram-generations themselves. Is that possible, Geordi?

Using wave guides, I could split a particle stream out of the matter/antimatter chamber and route it down through existing conduit into the Holodeck -- if it is accelerated to sufficient velocity that will quite literally wash away all the present holographic constructs -- the London buildings, the streets, the people, all gone... including Moriarty.
And Doctor Pulaski?
The particle stream will tear apart human flesh as well, that option is not acceptable.
Captain, I am suddenly sensing more order to the energy on the Holodeck -- as if one unifying force, one consciousness, is trying to bring it all into focus.
Captain, there is only one thing which can explain this. In programming Moriarty to defeat me, not Holmes, he had to be able to acquire something which I possess.
Exactly what?
Consciousness. He cannot defeat me without it.
Computer -- what happened?
Attitude and stabilization control of the Enterprise was momentarily transferred to Holodeck Two.
Data -- I think it's best if you and I returned to the Holodeck.
I will change into my uniform.
No -- I'll change into an appropriate costume. It seems he feeds on knowledge. Let's not give your nemesis any more information than we have to.
How did you shake the room?

The effect on him should be the same as it was on the crate.
Captain Picard.
Are you all right?
I'm fine. Except for being crammed full of crumpets.
Crumpets?
You look quite dashing, Captain. This is the first time I get to see you in action.
I hope you're not disappointed.
I'm sure I won't be.
You two have gotten awfully...
... chummy? Yes, this time together has been quite pleasant. I am a civilized abductor, Captain Picard. Civilized but still dangerous.
Bridge to Holodeck Control. Worf.
Here, sir.
Status. Has anything changed?
No.
Moriarty, you were conjured up to attempt to defeat Holmes here... and once that attempt is concluded -- win or lose -- your program has run its course, your existence is done.
Congratulations, Professor Moriarty, I capitulate to the better man -- your victory is well earned.

It's gone beyond that little game, Mister Data. And you'll note I no longer call you Holmes. Whatever I was when this began, I have grown. I am understanding more and more. And I am able to use the power at my fingertips.
I can affect this... this vessel, if that's where we are. I can also inflict bodily harm on you -- or on your doctor.
Yes -- I know that, Moriarty, but you haven't. You shook this ship because you wanted to get my attention -- you have it. So what is it you want?

The same thing you want for yourself. To continue to exist. If I destroy these surroundings, this vessel, can you say it doesn't matter to you? Interesting pun, don't you agree, for matter is what I am not. The computer has taught me that I am made up only of energy.

That... may not be completely true, Professor. This... which we call our "Holodeck" makes use of the same principle in another of our devices called a "transporter." By the year in which we live, humans have discovered that matter and energy are interchangeable. On this Holodeck energy has been converted to matter and thus you have substance, but only here.
And if I step off this Holodeck?
You would cease to be.
You are not alive, Moriarty, as I said you are only...
A holographic image, I know. But are you sure?
Yes.
Does he have life? He's a machine -- but is that all he is?
No. He is more.
Exactly. Is the definition of life "cogito ergo sum"? I think, therefore I am.
That's one possible definition.

It is the most important one and for me -- the only one that matters. You -- or someone -- asked your computer to program a nefarious fictional character from nineteenth century London -- and that is how I arrived... but I am no longer that creation. I am no longer that evil character, I have changed. I am alive -- I am aware of my own consciousness.
I'm responsible for the safety of this vessel and crew.
I want my existence. I want it out there just as you have yours.
That may not be possible.
Then you must do murder.
I cannot give you what you want.
Because you do not yet know how to convert Holodeck matter into a more permanent form.
That is true --
A pity. What I have seen -- what I have learned, fascinates me. I do not want to die.
And I do not want to kill you.
Madam, I have enjoyed your company.
It's been different.
Computer! "Arch."
Cancel override protocol, return control of the Holodeck to main computer. My fate is in your hands, as perhaps it always was.
Bridge, this is the Captain.
This is the bridge.
Number One, the situation is under control.
Aye, sir.
Professor Moriarty, this ship has vast, library memory capacity.
How well I know...

We will save this program of you. You will not be extinguished. We will save every aspect of you that exists now. And I promise you we will try to discover a way to bring you back in a form capable of leaving the Holodeck.
Then perhaps we'll meet again some day, Madam.
It may take many years. Time won't pass for you, but I may be an old woman.
But I'll still fill you with crumpets, Madam. I detest long good-byes. You have the arch.
As you wish. A short good-bye. Computer, save this program... then discontinue it for now.
Right up to the end, he never knew.
No. He didn't.
Know. Know what?
That he could leave the Holodeck.
But that's not possible.
I do not know how, but for Moriarty it was.
Then you lied when you told him he couldn't leave the Holodeck.
No, what the captain said was that we do not know how to convert Holodeck matter into a more permanent form. Which is true. Even after we review this program, we still may not have the answer.

Doctor, even with all his assurances -- that character was still Professor Moriarty. I will need to know a lot more about him before I allow him loose on my ship; he has, after all, made his reputation through cunning and deceit.
But how do you know he could leave the Holodeck?
Data.
The drawing?
No. The paper. This piece of paper was created as part of the Holodeck illusion. If it could leave the Holodeck, so too could Moriarty.
I'm impressed.
It is elementary, my dear Doctor... It is elementary.
Damaged?
Yes. A spar was cracked when the Enterprise was shaken. Otherwise she seemed to have weathered it nicely.
She's beautifully turned out, Lieutenant -- wonderful testimony to simpler times.
Yes -- it's just that I can't help thinking how badly it could have been damaged all because I misspoke a word.
Will she still sail?
Yes sir.
As will we.
Captain -- Starship Victory has arrived.
On my way, Number One.
Captain's log, stardate 41636.9. As feared, our examination of the seven year overdue Federation freighter, Odin -- disabled by an asteroid collision -- revealed no survivors.
However, three escape pods were missing, suggesting the possibility of survivors...
Ready to begin orbit of Angel One, Captain.
Make it so, Mister La Forge. What kind of place is this, Data?
Angel One is a class M planet, supporting carbon-based flora and fauna, sparsely populated with intelligent life forms... similar in technological development to mid-twentieth-century Earth.
Just like being marooned at home.

Assuming any survivors made it this far. Admittedly, it's the closest planet to the Odin. But the distance we've traveled in the past two days at warp one would've taken the Odin escape pods five months.
Five months, fourteen days, eleven hours, two minutes --
Thank you, Data.
-- and fifty-seven seconds.
Captain, we're receiving an audio signal from Angel One.

Starfleet was quite adamant that we maintain excellent diplomatic relations with this planet. Any other pertinent information before we reply, Mister Data? Their form of government would be a logical starting place.
Angel One has evolved into a constitutional oligarchy. It is governed by a parliamentary body consisting of six elected Mistresses, and headed by a female they refer to as "The Elected One."
It sounds very much like my own planet.
Klingons appreciate strong women.
How current is your information, Data?
A Federation vessel last visited this planet sixty-two years ago, Captain.
Except, let us hope, for the Odin escape pods. Since this is a female-dominated society, it might be more prudent if you made the initial contact, Counselor.
Please open hailing frequencies.
Hailing frequencies open.
This is Counselor Deanna Troi of the USS Enterprise.
I am Beata, The Elected One. How may we assist you, Counselor?
The Federation has neglected a visit to your planet for far too long. With your permission, we would like to correct that oversight.
We feel in no way neglected, Counselor. A diplomatic courtesy call is neither expected nor required.
We also come in search of possible survivors from one of our freighters.
A brief visit will be tolerated.
They've broken off transmission.
Ever feel like you're not really wanted?
That's their prerogative, Lieutenant. Prepare the away team, Number One.
Aye, aye, sir.
Where're you boys off to?
Skiing, sir. Our instructor has us scheduled for the Swiss Alps, sir.
Save us some deep powder.
No problem, sir. The Holodeck has all you'll ever need.
The away team is ready, Captain.
Angel One's position in this quadrant may become strategically vital. The hope at Starfleet is that some day this planet could become a part of the Federation.
We'll try to make a good impression, Captain.
Energize!
See that these matters are handled immediately.
